reference "tab:charles_visible_categories"

\end_inset

 for visible categories and Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:cexcategories"

\end_inset

 for the full consumer basket in the US CEX survey).
 The definition of visible consumption is often adjusted in these studies
 depending on the socio-cultural context.
 Omori-Smith ignore all visible consumption categories from the Charles
 et al study except that of clothing (including shoes)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OmoriSmithVisRace"

\end_inset

.
 Friehe-Mechtel used several definitions of the visibility basket to study
 the robustness of their results
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany"

\end_inset

.
 A study of the consumption in South Africa by Kaus chose a basket of products
 as close as possible to that in the Charles et al study
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The need for a survey to measure visibility of items in the basket is however
 necessary when conducting similar studies in developing world countries
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Khamis et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

 ask two key questions to respondents in an online survey conducted in India.
 First asked them how closely they needed to interact with their neighbour
 (with similar demographic characteristics) in order to observe above average
 spending for a list of items (Options were -‘1: No Interaction’, ‘2: Occasional
 Interaction’, ‘3: Friend’, ‘4: Close Friend’ or ‘5: No matter how much
 one Interacts’).
 An item where >20% respondents report 1 or 2 was considered a visible item.
 A second question asked them what they'll expect of the consumption of
 an item after a sudden 20 percent rise in their neighbor's income ‘1: Fall’,
 ‘2: Stay the same’, ‘3: Increase by less than 20 percent’, ‘4: Increase
 by 20 percent’ or ‘5: Increase by more than 20 percent’.
 The list of items in these questions attempted to match the consumption
 categories in the IHDS.
 An item is associated with higher income if more than 20% of respondents
 reported 2,3,4 or 5.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Visibility is a socio-cultural judgment - and the visibility basket from
 the developed world cannot be translated as such into disparate geographies
 and cultural environments of the developing world.
 One can arrive at wrong conclusions on visibile consumption for a consumer
 group if a visiblity basket was chosen from a different cultural environment.
 For example, hair-products may be associated with a higher visibility (and
 promise) in the developed world but in the developing world their purpose
 could be just utilitarian (poor quality of production, cultural factors
 etc.).
 Attributing lower visible consumption based on a low consumption of hair-produc
ts would thus be erroneous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another practical problem arises in the developing world because of the
 predominant use of recall method in expenditure survey.
 A relevant anomaly is the Deaton Paxson paradox(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonPaxsonParadox"

\end_inset

) - i.e.
 the observed decrease in food expenditure per head as household size rises
 (with constant outlay per head).
 The likely cause for the paradox is presence of errors correlated with
 household size in the data that results in possible overestimation of the
 consumption of recalled items
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GibsonDeatonPaxson"

\end_inset

.
 Caution must therefore be taken (or a correcton applied) when mixing expenditur
es from recall and diary methods.
\end_layout

